PAY ATTENTION to how much I emphasis the stretch (negative part) in EVERY movement, yes even the compound exercises. I can’t stress enough how important it is to open up during these exercises. If you can’t, then lower the weight and try again. A lot of people don’t realize but if you’re not opening your back up during your training, you can’t expect it to open up on stage. You’re understanding your ability to open your muscles up properly during training WILL reflect how you CAN or CANNOT open it up onstage. The reason I can always open my back up onstage like a parachute is because I emphasis that during EVERY back workout. 

Also, their is a big difference between full range of motion and over extending. Once that muscle can no longer be stretched or opened up is where the movement should end. Anything past that is considered over stretching and yes it can lead to compensation in other body parts which can lead to injury. Perfect example, look at how I execute my one arm DB row. #protips 

Hope this helps 💪🏻

17 weeks of TRT 🤠

A lot of people in the fitness industry have this notion that you can’t make improvements off a cycle, or being off a cycle makes it ok to slack off an eat shit and slack in the gym. 

The power of consistency in the sport is crucial! As you all know, building a solid physique is a marathon not a race. If you are an athlete of any kind, it is unacceptable and inexcusable to let your body go at anytime. If you want to be the best, it’s very important to beat at your craft everyday. Yes you can take your foot off the gas a bit in regards to lifting crazy heavy, but that doesn’t mean it’s ok to still not train hard. You can still maximize your workouts by doin supersets, dropsets, giant sets, cluster sets.

I only do 12-13 mins on the stairs post workout.. THATS ALL. You don’t need to kill yourself with cardio or restrict yourself to barely eating. I eat a lot, but all the foods I eat are the exact same foods I eat during PREP, just in more abundance. 

I allow myself 1 cheat meal every 2 weeks. It used to be every 3 weeks, but I noticed I stayed a touch fuller and less stringy when I did it every 2 weeks. Discipline is everything in this game, so if you keep the same mindset you do when you’re “dieting strict” year around, then you will always look good and have a respectable physique. Being lean also allows your body to function more optimally.

YOU DON’T NEED TO BE ON JUICE TO LOOK GOOD OR EAT CLEAN!! That’s a lazy ass lame excuse to justify having a sloppy work ethic. Guys don’t complain for not getting the results that you didn’t work for. I weigh myself every night, and I’m ALWAYS between 251-254lbs. Again, eating the same foods and being consistent will give you consistent results. 

If I can be on 4 different heart meds that slow down my heart rate and make it 10x harder to get a pump/ stay fuller,and still look like this, then so could you guys no problem! Believe in yourself, have a routine and don’t break that shit for fucking ANYBODY 👊🏻

🥶 My first #cryotherapy experience 🧊 
  ICE BATH VS. CRYOTHERAPY

The first thing I noticed within the first 30 seconds is how less invasive it was compared to an ice bath. This makes it a lot more realistic and easy for a lot of people to do on a more regular and ongoing routine for longer periods. Personally after doin ice/ cold baths 2-4 times a week for months on end, I simply just burned out. 

Ice baths have a lot more of a mental challenge to it as well, which can 100% be a good thing. It’s also cheaper, but not as easy or convenient. 

In my opinion I think they both have major benefits, so my personal recommendation would be to still incorporate both, and just rotate between the 2 as you see fit. ❄️ ❄️

LETS TALK GIANT SETS!!

WHAT IS A GIANT SET?
A giant set is when you perform 3 or more exercises back to back with no rest. So yes as you would guess, the weight will need to be adjusted in order to keep form on point and not sloppy.
So you’ll notice I’m going exceptionally light on the last 2 exercises.
 
DO I DO THIS EVERYWORKOUT?
No, I do them as I feel fit. It’s a great way to maximize a pump and tearing down muscle fibers without having to go crazy heavy. BUT, with that said it won’t stimulate your CNS like goin all out on one movement at a time. So it’s great to incorporate here and there.

DO YOU GET A BETTER PUMP DOIN THESE ?
Honestly yes, that’s one thing you will notice is a skin tearing pump, and also a lot of lactic acid build up lol. But again it’s a great way to maximize a movement and increase blood flow to a muscle without having to risk injury. 

I never see people perform these, but I’m telling you they feel great and are very beneficial. Throw this concept into your next workout, you won’t regret it 👊🏻

If you’re anything like me and have issues being shoulder dominant, than I HIGHLY recommend pre fatiguing your chest with a machine fly movement as your first exercise. I like to rotate between 2 arm fly and 1 arm fly week to week. This helps maximize the stimulation on the chest and keeps it off the shoulders. 

YES, you will be slightly weaker after doing this exercise first. But remember, this is bodybuilding not powerlifting. The idea is always to get maximum stimulation from a muscle, opposed to just lifting as heavy as you can and getting all kinds of other muscle groups involved. 

It’s better to start with flys and stimulate the chest, then proceed to your next movement and continue to feel constant stimulation in your chest, even if you are slightly weaker. The central thesis of your training shouldn’t be revolves around strength anyways. I’ve been the strongest guys have the ugliest physiques lol. Personally, that aspect is just an added bonus. 

Trust me, I promise you will see much more efficient growth this way even if you aren’t as strong deeper into the workout, and it will help prevent injury. Anytime your connected mentally with the desired muscle your training, you’ll understand the amount you lift isn’t a priority whatsoever. YES, being strong is great, but lifting accurately with full range of motion is much more important in this sport.

I have never and will never be the strongest pro bodybuilder, but my ability to connect to a body part is what will get you ahead. The idea is to stimulate a muscle group as much as possible in order to recruit more nutrients to that area so it can recover and grow. Don’t overcomplicate it 👊🏻 💪🏻

How to perform a PROPER dip (for chest)
 🔥 @bioxperformancenutrition #tipoftheday 🔥 

#1) flare elbows out
#2) roll shoulders slightly forward 
#3) keep that chest popped up (even though your back is rounded) (like a front relaxed pose for the bodybuilders)
#4) shift glutes back 
#5) keep chin tucked in
#6) keep a tight range of motion, make sure you’re not going to low (this will ensure you’re keeping pressure off the shoulders and on the chest)

🦵 🦵 DO’S & DON’TS tutorial of barbell SQUATS!!! 🏋️‍♂️

✅ DO…
-Always stretch and warm up your hips, knees, lower back and quads prior to squatting (especially when you get as old as me 😝)
-initiate movement from the hip, NOT the knee
-make sure to brace your core and keep your chest up at all points of the movements
-emphasize glute contraction to help keep weight centered and pressure away from the knees 
-always keep toes pointed slightly outwards (unless you’re bull legged) 
-focus on form and hitting 90 degrees, not “ass to grass” where you can round your back out and cause a slew of unnecessary injuries 
-always keep weight centered primarily on heel to mid foot
-always control the negative part of the movement (coming down) this will help your posterior chain engage and fire off correctly 

❌ DO NOT…
-let your knees collapse inwards
-round out your back 
-your toes come up (this isn’t a smith squat)
-don’t let your feet flare outwards or inwards 
-avoid butt wink (which you won’t have to worry about if you go 90 degrees)
-DONT LOOK DOWN!! Always straight, wherever your head is pointing, the rest of your body will follow!!
